AGI - For the first time in literature, the Hospital San Camillo Forlanini of Rome has performed a TAVI intervention in TAVI - plant from the femoral artery of a new aortic bioprotesis within a previous damaged aortic bioprotesis - in a patient affected by the rare Morquio Syndrome.
&nbsp;
The intervention, carried out successfully by Dr. Francesco De Felice and Dr. Diana Chin of the Interventist Cardiology team represented the only valid therapeutic option for patient survival. Morquius Syndrome (type IV mmucopolysischaridesis) is a rare genetic disease, with an incidence of 1 to 300,000.
&nbsp;
It involves the accumulation of complex sugars (glycosaminoglycans) in the body, causing musculoskeletal problems, including a mild stature and compromising the functionality of vital organs such as the heart and lungs. The patient, only 53 years old, already undergoing numerous orthopaedic interventions, had received in 2017 a first TAVI plant to correct the severe narrowing of the aorta. In 2023, following an aggravation of stenosis, it was treated with an aortic vavuloplasty. At that point, the patient was considered at very high risk for a new surgery or a further TAVI in TAVI.
&nbsp;
Following a recent clinical deterioration, the woman arrived at the San Camillo ER for acute heart failure. Here Cardiologa Dr. Vania Chianta has made a rapid echocardiographic diagnosis, identifying an aortic valve dysfunction with severe stenosis and heart failure. After stabilizing the heart failure picture by medical and nursing staff of Cardiology Long, a TAC performed by the radiology team headed by Dr. Vitaliano Buffa confirmed the technical feasibility of a TAVI intervention in TAVI through transfemoral access.
&nbsp;
The multidisciplinary Heart Team confirmed the latter as the only therapeutic option, since an isolated medical therapy would have had infamous outcomes. The intervention was successfully performed by Dr. Francesco De Felice and Dr. Diana Chin of the UOS of Interventistic Cardiology related to the UOC of Cardiology, directed by Prof. Domenico Gabrielli, with the anesthetic support of the UOC of Cardioanestesia (Anesthesia and Reanimation of the Cardio-Toraco-Vascolare Department) directed by Prof. Elio D'Avino.
&nbsp;
The surgeons to implant the new heart prosthesis in the patient have used transfemoral access in local anesthesia to reduce risks. All under the continuous monitoring of Dr. Davide Cristofani. Basically the support of the nursing staff (Dario Lolli, Diego Roviti, Mauro Ruscito) and technician (Sabrina Saraceni).
&nbsp;
The procedure was successfully completed, without complications, and the patient was followed by the UTIC team - Cardiological Intensive Therapy Unit - until discharge after a few days. Although the percutane replacement of the aortic valve is increasingly widespread, TAVI interventions in TAVI remain complex and rare procedures, requiring high technical expertise and meticulous planning. Dr. De Felice commented: "The positive result obtained in this case confirms as a multidisciplinary approach by high-level professionals, assisted by a company strategic direction attentive to the needs of health professionals and users, allows the Sanitaria San Camillo Forlanini Company to confirm itself as a leading center in the eroding the most suitable care for users who turn to the structure". &nbsp;
